If you've only ever experienced or heard of hardcore drinkers (the ones that drink and drive, or get into fights, or end up killing themselves), then I don't blame you.
If you have your shit together and know the difference between knowing when you're buzzed, when you're drunk, when you're *really* drunk and when you're shitfaced as well as knowing when to stop then you're golden.
Also finding an alcohol type that you genuinely enjoy helps. I don't get people who drink for the sake of getting drunk rather than having drunkeness as a fun biproduct of enjoying something smooth/sweet/complex/etc and of good quality.
For me I know I'm in a good spot when the edges of my vision are just a little blurrier than normal. I laugh at more stupid stuff, I get chatty and willing to sing out loud when I'm far too shy to do so.
By the same token at that point I can walk around just fine. I can make my way to the bathroom and back without causing any issues. I know driving is totally out of the question, as with any machine that could be dangerous.
As said, this isn't for everyone, but responsible drinking's great. I drink a couple of times a month, almost always after a week at work to help mellow out, although I only occasionally use it for my writing if I need to be in a slightly more outlandish headspace for whatever reason. Hell, the thing I wrote that was the most interesting while drunk was a harrowing, nightmarish story of a character losing the two people he loved the most (wife and best friend) in two really grisly ways. I'd NEVER write that usually but looking back it was a good way to delve into spaces I just don't like going. I know I'm capable of it now when the idea of tragic, senseless death was just a no-go zone.
